Heres how we could make a chart-spec using Python:

import altair as alt
from vega_datasets import data
iris = data.iris()
p2 = alt.Chart(iris).mark_point().encode(
    x='petalLength',
    y='petalWidth',
    color='species'
)

Heres an equivalent way using R.

Note that we seem to have to use r_to_py() - so we might consider exporting that function from reticulate.

iris_new <- 
  iris %>%
  rename(
    sepal_length = Sepal.Length,
    sepal_width = Sepal.Width,
    petal_length = Petal.Length,
    petal_width = Petal.Width,
    species = Species
  )
  
p <- alt$Chart(r_to_py(iris_new))$mark_point()$encode(
    x = "petal_length",
    y = "petal_width",
    color = "species"
)

htmlwidget

To be an htmlwidget, we need three things:

  1. A collection of library files, with a manifest.
  2. A function to bind the widget to R.
  3. Some to bind the widget to Javascript.

Lets start with what we will need for files. We have an Rmd that downloads the files and puts them into place.

We now need a function that binds the widget to R. This function is called vegalite(), and it takes an altair$Chart() object as its main argument.

Finally, we need a Javascript-binding bit of code. I only partly understand it, but it works.

If Ive done this right, then this should work:

vegalite(p)

And now for something completely different

Lets follow this Altair tutorial on selection interactions.

plot <- alt$Chart(r_to_py(mtcars))$mark_point()$encode(
    x = 'mpg:Q',
    y = 'hp:Q',
    color = 'cyl:N'
)

vegalite(plot)

Now, lets create a brush and bind it to the plot.

brush <- alt$selection_interval()  # selection of type "interval"

plot <- plot$properties(selection = brush)

vegalite(plot)

Lets make the brush do something interesting:

plot <- 
  alt$Chart(r_to_py(mtcars))$mark_point()$encode(
    x = 'mpg:Q',
    y = 'hp:Q',
    color = alt$condition(brush, 'cyl:N', alt$value('lightgray'))
  )$properties(selection = brush)

vegalite(plot)

For our next trick, link a couple of plots together.

# also twiddling with some code-styling
plot_basic <-
  alt$Chart(
    r_to_py(mtcars)
  )$mark_point(
  )$encode(
    y = 'hp:Q',
    color = alt$condition(brush, 'cyl:N', alt$value('lightgray'))
  )$properties(
    width = 250,
    height = 250,
    selection = brush
  )

plot_left <- 
  plot_basic$encode(
    x = 'disp:Q'
  )

plot_right <- 
  plot_basic$encode(
    x = 'mpg:Q'
  )

plot_compound <- alt$hconcat(plot_left, plot_right)

vegalite(plot_compound)
